    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yo i was doing some sprints today and my legs felt like they were on fire lol. can u explain what actually happens with the lactic acid when u push that hard? like how does it get made and how does it go away?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When you sprint, your muscles demand energy faster than oxygen can be delivered, leading to anaerobic respiration. This rapid energy production creates lactic acid as a byproduct, which is what gives you that burning sensation. The body doesn't actually build up lactic acid; rather, it converts pyruvate into lactate to regenerate necessary energy substrates. As you recover, your liver and muscles convert this lactate back into glucose through a process called the Cori cycle.",
